snippet.textDisplay:
NO FUCKING THANKS!!! Games like Bloodborne, Red Dead Redemption, Eldin Ring, Dark Souls, Assassin's Creed, God of War...Games that come off as slow, boring, and needlessly complicated as fuck when it comes to gameplay. The overealism and over powered NPC's...I hate it when games pull this shit. 

I'd spend one or two hours in one area just trying to level up to beat someone at the beginning of the game. That's how it was in Bloodborne. I beat it eventually, but it sure as hell wasn't fucking worth it. 

I want FUN games. StarFox 64, Mario 64, Lolipop Chainsaw, Kingdom Hearts 2, Xenosaga 3, LOZ: Hyrule Warriors, GTA San Andreas, Dragonball Z: Kakorot, Super Smash Bros...Now those are fun. Easy to get the hang of, straight forward, and sometimes fast paced. I don't have to overthink a damn thing, just go with it.

snippet.textDisplay:
I'm almost 40 years old and I don't know that I've ever LOVED video games. I've also never felt a huge sense of accomplishment from beating them either. 
This game is different. I went to Hirata Estate the second I got the bell, and fought lady butterfly way before I should have. I got violently angry. That miserable old woman clapped my cheeks at least 50 times. When I finally beat her I screamed. My heart was racing,  and my hands were shaking. 
I have never felt that from a video game before. 
It is excellent.

snippet.textDisplay:
Cheers for covering this. I almost missed this in the Steam Winter sale and was just curious about it üëç 
There's me thinking that this could be a sort of resurrection of the good old Tenchu games, but nope, it wasn't to be. Only thing really putting me off getting this game is the hand holding crud in regards with the platforming. And I'm so surprised at that sort of hand holding tedium being in a FromSoftware title. 
The main issue for me is how there's button pressing to jump and scale. I dislike that greatly. I'd much rather it be more manual and open to error if you do it wrong. That bit there in the opening of the video 0:23 shows just how easy the scaling is. Press a button and jump there, or there, or there. WAY too easy. It's very rewarding in the Tenchu games when you land in the right spot, especially when using stealth. As per usual from that developer though, the combat looks challenging and wicked, so no doubt this will be a huge hit for the fans of Demon / Dark Souls,  Bloodborne and Elden Ring.

snippet.textDisplay:
beating the game and then going back through in NG+ while I was 100%ing the game really put into perspective how much you learned over the course of your first playthrough. I remember bashing my head against the wall trying to beat lady butterfly and Ashina Elite (yes I struggled with the Ashina Elite), and yet in NG+ I found them shockingly easy to beat just because my understanding of the core mechanics had grown so much. 
If souls games are about learning how to beat a certain boss, sekiro is about learning how to be a strong fighter and applying that to bosses. Like stated in the video, each boss teaches you a unique way of tackling enemies, and it will take some time to learn those mechanics, but once you do you'll be able to apply them in the future, it's an incredibly satisfying gameplay loop. If you're not looking for a challenging game, maybe go elsewhere, but anyone that's beaten a souls game should have the stubbornness required to press on.

snippet.textDisplay: How can you put out a review praising how good a game is, then say your not good at it. This isn't Mario Cart. If your not good at this game, you don't finish this game. Hell, you don't even get 10percent into this game. In my opinion, the fact it doesnt have dlc proves the way I feel is more accurate. And that is, it's a really well made game, made infinitely annoying by unforgiving mechanics. You have to be too perfect, and you have to master the mechanics to beat the game. So I give it a 5 out of 10. Zero replay value, zero co-op, and mechanics that you have no choice but to master.

snippet.textDisplay:
Unlike DS, there‚Äôs no real way to grind up before all the tough as nails bosses to get some extra edge in, and beneficial consumables are way more limited, so most fights come down to pure skill, which seems admirable at first, but feels way more like trial and error. DS felt unforgiving but still fair, here it feels like the game is being way more sadistic like a rigged carnival game.

Jumping and running around with a sword is still fun though!

snippet.textDisplay: Blatant lies in this video. This game is not anywhere this good and fair. It's repetitive, small, and boring. Combat must click with you. If not - you will suffer. There is no other option to play the game except the way developers incline you to. It's unfair. I've beaten every boss except father owl and ishin the sword saint. I would've beaten them too but got tired. There is almost no room for invention in the late game with bosses - you just freaking memorize by heart their patterns and try not to make any single mistake. It is not fun.

snippet.textDisplay: First I would like to say that I‚Äôm new to playing video games. I have played a couple here and there and I was never any good really. I gave gaming a try when I was a kid and Nintendo had just came out so this has been a long time ago( think Mike Tyson‚Äôs Punchout, original Super Mario, Contra, Castlevania and Top Gun) so it‚Äôs a long time ago lol.                       I just recently bought my first gaming console (Xbox One S) and I‚Äôm still learning the controls and what they do. I got Sekiro Shadows Die Twice because I saw some of the gameplay of Ghost of Tsushima and really want to play it but they don‚Äôt make it for Xbox One but, I must say that I am really enjoying this game.                         Look I don‚Äôt know a whole lot about the tech specs or whatever but, this is super fun to play. I don‚Äôt care that it‚Äôs 30 frames per second because I have no idea what that means. To be honest, I don‚Äôt really care either because I just want to have fun. I have had this game for about 3 weeks and whenever I get stuck on some part I just put in another game and play it until I get stuck and come back to it. It takes me a while to get things done right but, I have fun doing it and that‚Äôs all that matters to me. I may never beat the game but, I don‚Äôt care just as long as I have fun and the story is enjoyable.

snippet.textDisplay: Came back to this video to compare it to the review of Ghost of Tsushima.  TBH  this is the review that convinced me to buy the game, and now it's my favorite game of all time.  There is no comparable combat system.  Not in  dark souls or in bloodborne or in any other game I've ever played.  This is the best for me.  The world is a fascinating blend of Japanese mythology, and its an incredible success.  The story is good.  But this game, more than anything, always comes back to the steel on steel combat.  I've beaten in five times throughout this year, always coming back to it a while after the previous play through because I start thinking of the combat and the satisfaction of having a good clash of parries and attacks.
snippet.textOriginal: Came back to this video to compare it to the review of Ghost of Tsushima.  TBH  this is the review that convinced me to buy the game, and now it's my favorite game of all time. The world is a fascinating blend of Japanese mythology, and its an incredible success.  The story is good.  But this game, more than anything, always comes back to the steel on steel combat. snippet.textDisplay: Stick with it guys it gets better, I play for a couple weeks got stuck and left the game for a couple weeks. At first I wasnt able to get past gyubo, but now I just beat Lady Butterfly, Seven spears, and I'm currently trying to fight Genichiro. This game is amazing. When you get a new skill mastered or perfectly time most of your deflects it makes you feel like you just got a super power. Stick with it and you will get past that wall you hit and this game has alot of beautiful moments worth seeing but it definitely makes you earn them lol

snippet.textDisplay: For everyone coming from soulsborne games: in Sekiro you can‚Äôt grind (you can‚Äôt extra farm to increase stats). However, I noticed the boss fights have somewhat more complex and various strategies. You will go from trying to dodge / block at random to knowing what to do for any of the boss‚Äô moves. Honestly, it‚Äôs not a game where you become stronger as a character, it‚Äôs a game where you see yourself become stronger as a player.

It's a shame too cause everything about this game is awesome but the insane difficulty just ruins it. My suggestion to the devs of this game is add an update with an easy and med diff mode so those of us who are not game gods have a chance to experience this game. Just my 2 cents.

snippet.textDisplay: I really enjoy the game. Oniwa (Spear guy on horse) was a really fun fight for me that I enjoyed a lot. Took a few tries but I won after adapting. Then Ginichro was the msot challenging boss fight I've done but before I did take him on I got 2 skills and made sure I was prepared to take him on and after an hr against him I won but it was really satisfying and fun. I hated the seven spear good. Was ragging all kinds after fighting him. But I beat him and he fell off a cliff, that was worth it. What I did get from that fight was a better understanding of combat etc and it really showed as I took on other bosses and enemies.

snippet.textDisplay: Just beat the game. The one thing I think people should know before buying it is that Sekiro is NOT a Dark Souls/Bloodborne RPG with a Japanese setting. snippet.textDisplay:
I'd recommend this game to someone who wants a challenge and a new experience compared to From Soft's other titles. Sekiro's punishing but fair, I never really felt cheated by the games mechanics and even though there's similarities to Dark souls or bloodborne this is a totally different ball park.
One of the great new mechanics is your prosthetic arm which is your second mode of transport, (the grapple hook) and your second swappable weapon, the attachments range from loaded Shuriken to a flame thrower and even a shield. The fact sekiro has a very clear story line with a set and voiced protagonist is a nice change too. Just saying though, if you're wondering if it has many fantasy elements, you're in luck.
The game gets pretty weird, fairly fast. And I love every bit. Very immersive, very rewarding and the overall thrill of learning how to tackle new enemies and killing them is exhilarating. Keep an eye out for secrets and good luck.

snippet.textDisplay: Finally finished it today.  A great game, but definitely not in the same niche as Dark Souls / Bloodborne imo.  Lack of customization / build variety hurts replayability, and no multiplayer feels like a missed opportunity.  The story was interesting, but being told everything outright was way less compelling than trying to figure out stuff on your own, like in the Souls games.  Also, while the level design is GREAT, it's also VERY EASY to miss entire sections of the game since the camera doesn't let you look straight up or down, and sometimes you have to grapple straight up or fall straight down to get to the next area completely blind.  I had to do a lot of googling/wikiing to find the path this game, and that usually means there aren't enough breadcrumbs.

snippet.textDisplay:
To anyone who didnt buy it yet, it has two bad sides only.

First of all ng+ has nothing new, so its just the same game but a bit harder. I was really dissapointed with this cause the game isnt even that long, and it cost so much.

Second con is the story. No spoilers, but the story get pretty generic and repetitive at times. Some elements are re used for no reason and it seems like FromSoft just didnt bother to make more content. That said, I read the interview with Miyazaki he did with Famitsu. Miyazaki said that he wanted to take a new direction and I respect that. 

Overall, amazing game, average replayability. I guess 8.5/10

Oh and its really difficult ofc

snippet.textDisplay: Personally after putting 40hrs in the game already a tip I would give people just starting is to approach this game with the mindset of bloodborne, where you're aggressive against the smaller mobs and a tad more conservative against the bosses until you've learned their moveset and then unleash all hell on them. snippet.textDisplay:
TL;DR: This is a polished PS2 game; you‚Äôve seen it before: Giant, satirical bosses who are supposed to be scary to kids who are the type of people to have trouble crossing the street, little to no customization, no multiplayer, tiring map design that looks like a mish mash of the others but with a different architectural style, bad and cliche story, probably little to no DLC or paid DLC, bad and static weather system, barely destructible environments, formulaic music design and writing.

Just a bare bones effort, really. Another drop in the bucket. Have fun, kids!
snippet.textOriginal:
TL;DR: This is a polished PS2 game; you‚Äôve seen it before: Giant, satirical bosses who are supposed to be scary to kids who are the type of people to have trouble crossing the street, little to no customization, no multiplayer, tiring map design that looks like a mish mash of the others but with a different architectural style, bad and cliche story, probably little to no DLC or paid DLC, bad and static weather system, barely destructible environments, formulaic music design and writing.

Just a bare bones effort, really. Another drop in the bucket. Have fun, kids!

snippet.textDisplay: I really like how From changes up the gameplay with each new Souls-like franchise even though all of their games share similar gameplay mechanics. Dark Souls had a focus on slower, defense/shield-oriented & magic gameplay, Bloodborne‚Äòs focus on quick-paced evasion & parrying, and Sekiro with quick-paced deflection & stealth. It still feels like a Souls game but it‚Äôs different enough in its mechanics that it keeps the genre fresh. It takes some time to realize that deflecting blows is usually better than dodging or rolling out of the way but once you get the hang of it, the game isn‚Äôt quite as difficult than when you were first starting the game (not to say the game gets much easier; it definitely still has that Souls challenge). I can‚Äôt wait to see other new iterations From comes up with in the future.

As far as the people that say "what about the sense of accomplishment you get when games are harder".  WTF are you talking about, IT'S A GAME!  Why are you taking it that seriously?  


If your sense of accomplishment from a game outweighs the rage quitting and controller throwing then more power to you, I do not understand that though.  This is completely beside the point that when I play a game I want to feel like a powerful badass and it's impossible to feel that way when you're getting killed every few minutes.  I'm a pathetic weakling in real life, I don't have to play a video game character to get that same feeling.

snippet.textDisplay: Where were the cons? So let me give you some of the cons as a long time From Software fan. This is a very very dumb down version of dark souls. So being used to how dark souls is played and naturally picked up on the game and was getting through it fairly easy. However they do certain things in this game that you don‚Äôt see in other souls games that make this game cheaply hard. 1 The controls are all over the place. I think O is to dodge X to jump which is used to get over sweeps L1 is guard and parry R1 is attack. Once they start adding in dual button move and buttons for the Prosthetic your hands are all over the controller it feels like I‚Äôm handling the damn rubik‚Äôs cube. Nioh accomplished a much better fighting system. 3 My biggest issue with the game is that once you fight characters who are boss level or even black knight a equivalent from dark souls games they start having attacks that lock on and home to you. E.g if an enemy does a drop kick in midair and you see it coming you decide to dodge before they land  that dodge becomes useless because it turns towards you like a damn heat seeking missile. So dodge is almost useless it‚Äôs hit or miss.On top of that if you‚Äôre fighting a level boss your prosthetic becomes useless because you get in this confined area where you can‚Äôt grab or anything and get out of danger meanwhile they‚Äôre throwing fucking lightning bolts and illusions at you and all you can do is swing the sword because your grappling hook is almost useless now. So yeah it‚Äôs hard but it feels cheap. I only start dying once I get to boss level enemies as a matter fact I went to whole time without getting Dragonrot until I got to the damn boss because they attacks home to  you.

snippet.textDisplay:
I tried it and it left me deeply unsatisfied, the best part of souls games to me was the excitement of getting new gear, every hardship i faced while exploring was rewarded when i found some badass armor set or weapon, in sekiro you face a much higher difficulty level and have to explore far more carefully just to find the same boring consumables...and also i dislike the 1v1 focus of this fighting system


I played the game for 5-6 hours and after a while i just decided to quit because nothing was pushing me to continue, i knew that the sword i was using was gonna be the same one throughout the whole thing, the shitty orange rags i was wearing were gonna stay there for the whole duration of the adventure and the biggest variations i was gonna see were the prosthetic arm skills which are quite limited in use due to their cost...so yeah, the balance between hardship and motivation was completely skewed in my opinion and i very much hope fromsoft will get back on the soulslike formula with their next release

snippet.textDisplay:
It doesn't feel like a Ds, Wich is good We already had 4 of that, But rather a Re Thought Conception of the next Heir of Ds.
The mobility Feels insane and this is their first game with Mobile Mehanics like these. They nailed every aspect they have put in.
You can do so many things, i literaly Felt like a Strategist while playing it, looking down on my enemies, looking for path to take them down, looking trough my inv to see if theres anything to help me.
It harder than ever, but to be honest, i rather do to sekiro then Ds, DS had Magic, Block, Roll, And Attack...
Sekiro is like... Stealt, Deathblows from every direction, prostethics, sword play, dash, jump, Hook, Block, Deflect, Shurikens, Axe, Flamethrower, Fckn Fireworks, Whatever you like...
I just love the combat

snippet.textDisplay:
You addressed a lot of my own feelings about how this game is approached.  In a way it's closer to Ninja Gaiden than it is to Tenchu, in that you have to know exactly how you play and what you can do.
It's also similar conceptually to Mega Man, where finding and using the right tool for the job turns an impossible task doable, along with a shared multitude of paths, of which you have to figure out the best order to take.
Even its odd approach to stealth is based on positioning yourself to the best possible way to kill everyone quickly, on top of picking and choosing who to kill first in order to make the rest of the fight more manageable.
Sekiro is another great Miyazaki game, and one that finally gave the guy a chance to do something new while hitting the same stylistic and narrative beats that made Hidetaka Miyazaki and From Software household names.

Bought the PC version and the first few hours are brutal but then it becomes easy AF. I would even say that it's actually the easiest From Soft game (since the Soulsborne inception) once you get used to the mechanics. The boss that gave me the most fit was that giant monkey who also surprised the hell out of me as well, it was so out of place and felt like an old school boss. Played the hell out of this game for 3 days now (45 plus hours in total). My only regret is the ending I've got so far, turned out to be the saddest one. =( 
Need to get the other three specially the happy one: but I have work and will try again doing another run maybe relegating 1 to 2 hour per day and going full game mode on Friday night and the weekends.

snippet.textDisplay: The game destroys your soul but, and this is a big but, when the combat system clicks for you boy oh boy you start to become a killing machine. A blade god deflecting and one shotting fools like it's your job.  This game is amazing, a masterpiece. It has some of the same elements from last soulsborne games such a bonfires, in this game they are called idols. Basically it has some of the same items with effects from past games but with different names. One of my new favorite games of all time. Still love dark souls 3 hopefully they make a dark souls 4 someday. But if this is the type of games they are going forward with I'm okay with that. Mayne we will see a sekiro 2 or bloodborne 2 before a dark souls 4. Either way anyone of those games will be amazing in the future. Fromsoft knows how to make amazing singleplayer games. 10/10.

snippet.textDisplay:
Played through Dark Souls, never bothered with the Sequels (got the trilogy collection now, might as well).
Tanked 40 hours on Bloodborne before even facing the first main Boss (Father Gascoigne), loved every second of it.
First 8 hours into Sekiro, just near the Hirata Estate, I've made more progress in the story faster than I've ever have in the other games, yet it doesn't feel rewarding for making the hurdle gameplay-wise. Sure, there's no hand-holding the way grinding to one-hit KO strength in XP-based RPGs gets you, but the way strategy is coaxed out of you in Sekiro isn't very creative. For example, the Monkey Axe makes the Shield grunts an easy deathblow, but having tried alternative tactics, the axe is the ONLY way to kill them. After training with Hanbei, no other trick works: you can't dodge blade side and hit them exposed, you can't kick-jump over their shield and pull a Helmsplitter (like LoZ TP hidden skills), nor can you straightforward knock their posture. My expectation was this: it'll be Hellah difficult to whittle down these goons, but it's still possible, and getting the special tools will make my life easier for it! What I got instead: don't bother getting creative, there's only one way to skin this cat, and we still won't tell you! At least in Bloodborne, I can sneak, stun, Parry, and shoot my foes with varying degrees of success, but that just isn't so in Sekiro. I might even finish the game soon even, but I'm not sure the story will be all that worth it.

snippet.textDisplay:
Is this a before you buy video? Or a just buy it right now cos it's awesome video? Cos you didn't mention any cons apart from the performance which it's still HDR, but you didn't mention things like. 

1: Everytime you die all enemys come back to life, and you're put back in the last sculptor symbol which maybe was far away and right before a huge path of hard enemies. 

2: Not being able to save your progress twice on the same sculptor symbol when you clear a path full of hard enemys cos if you rest they're alive again.

3: Objects and weapons are scattered randomly without letting the player know where they are, cos tips from random characters are also scattered and hidden, which means you could spend hours and hours exploring and still not find some weapon or valuable object which is key to beat some kind of enemy and that, at least for me, sucks and seems like a huge waste of time.

4: Everytime you wanna fit a prosthetic weapon or even check your abilities menu to get another one, guess where you have to go? Back again to the sculpor to fit the weapon and to a sculptor symbol just to acces the abilities menu but if you go back to a previous symbol to do it, cos they might be about to kill you and still you didn't find any new one, all what you did, all enemys and paths you cleared that took you, let's say two hours to clear, well, they're again alive and you go back to two hours ago and that including that your half an hour playing to get half exp is erased everytime you die and that makes it feel like if you were stuck on a loop, which is super annoying.

In Resume this is the most annoying and irritating game I've ever played and I only reached the second General.

snippet.textDisplay:
Completely agree with you, the game is difficult but, unlike Dark Souls that is based around you trying different items, weapons, and armor to finish your enemy, Sekiro focuses more on learning the deep moveset, mastering it's reflection system, and looking for the perfect moment to strike all in to break your foe's poise and reach that apex moment of the incredibly satisfying execution. It makes you feel like a real shonin in training, progressively getting better and learning to use the skills given to you. 

Honestly, when I first fought Genichiro after the first area, died countless times trying to best him, then saw his badass second form before immediately dying and getting thrown back to the start, I only felt more determined. Because I knew that If I was just a bit faster, dodge just right, block at the perfect time, and find his weak spot I could win. And I did, and it felt so damn good. You notice it too, the more you go through a boss and learn how to fight them they only get easier and become less daunting as victory peaks over the horizon into your sight. You only need to get there.

I do miss the customization from the other Souls-like games though, I've played through all of Bloodborne and Dark Souls 3 with their DLC's (Loved it all) and I honestly think that their aesthetics, lore, incredibly unique items, and weapons are some things that can never really be replicated outside of their franchises. This is a definite welcome change of pace though. Great game in my book and I can't wait to throw a hundred more hours into it. I hear you get to decapitate a giant monkey, don't mind if I do.

snippet.textDisplay: If darksouls and bloodborne can merge together this would be it! Sekiro is actually faster than both games patience is absolutely required to beat certain bosses while oppressive spamming is helpful for others. Lots of content to unpack as well and exploration is highly rewarding. Main complaint during combat is the CAMERA some bosses will drive you insane here.  Perhaps my positioning was off for those that gave me trouble here but the lock-on will automatically disengage if you get pushed to a wall etc forcing you to reset the lock-on which could cause you to face the complete opposite direction of the boss eating your health bar. If the camera had some work done I'd say this game is near perfect gameplay otherwise. Stealth, combos, dodges, parries you name it this game has it!

snippet.textDisplay: This is by far the hardest of the soulsborne games in my opinion. I love all the games under that umbrella, even the souls like games made by other companies, like Nioh. To be honest (and without trying to brag too much ;) ), I'm actually pretty good at the soulsborne games. When DS3 came out, I 100% it (this is obviously before DLC) with just 13 deaths overall to bosses (11 of which were to the Nameless King). I got into speedrunning because of that game (nowhere near as good as the big names in SR though). Because of this, I thought I would at least be decent at Sekiro off the bat. Nope, it kicked my butt hard, and still does. I'm finally at a point in skill where I might fight a mini-boss without dying... might... This game is stupid hard, I haven't even beaten Genichiro yet. When people say this is a good entry point into the series I would have to disagree. Literally any of the other souls games are drastically easier than this game, to me at least. It might be just that my personal play style is more suited to Bloodborne and DS3, but holy cow the difference in difficulty, again to me, is basically night and day.

snippet.textDisplay: So far I'm throughly enjoying this game. It feels like a thoughtful, natural diversion from the soulsborne formula. Though I believe its quite flawed, the bosses are lacking (especially compared to the soulsborne bosses) the voice acting is stale and the enemy variety seems weak. But I love it, some things I think it does right is the combat, it feels very responsive, quick and engrossing, the setting, I love the aesthetic of feudal japan with the architecture and the interiors looking amazing, the prosthetics, dragonrot, the revive system, the grappling hook and the swordplay are smart editions. I haven't finished the game and cant wait to see where it goes next!

snippet.textDisplay: I honestly miss the leveling system. This one's way too frustrating reminds me of Ninja Blade which is also game from from software.  That game made quick time events where you had to push the button prompt in unbelievable QuickTime where wasn't fun and you had a rewind the cutscene constantly. The repetition of the game, kind of kills it the enjoyment. Like the Caged up ogre whatever it is  when I beat it I didn't have that feeling of accomplishment it was more like I got rid of that annoying thing . The worst thing is that you would be able to one-hit-kill the weaker enemies later on in Dark Souls but with this one you'll never get it to that point at least that's what it seems. So the difficulty level at the beginning is probably just going to increase and never get easier so it'll be frustrating all the way through. At least that's what I'm thinking but I hope not.

Well it's not really a "mistake" to play it on PS4, I mean ask everybody that thinks Bloodborne is the best game ever. The game performs the same as BB and DS3 on consoles. I get being disappointed because From can't put a game with 60 fps on console but if you played the other games on console you'll be fine.

Last year's goty also didn't run at 60. I'd say if you can choose the PC version and you don't mind playing on PC you should go ahead and get it there. I personally played DS3 a billion times on pc with 60 fps and played Bloodborne on console after and I simply like playing on console better for reasons that have nothing to do with performance.

snippet.textDisplay: To whoever is thinking of getting this game but is scared or worried about the difficulty. I say GET IT. I have tried the souls games but have not been able to beat em. The closest i have gotten is bloodborne. But this game is fast, fluid, the combat is beautiful, the art style and the way it all unfolds. Its like a puzzle sometimes. Knowing what to use and when. The parry is the best thing i've seen here. Once you get the hang of it you feel like a complete and total badass. This is the most fair game out there. It doesnt hold your hand but it gives you everything you need to overcome something. This game also seems to tell you to just be patient. Everytime i was patient and took my time with the bosses, was on my toes to parry, and not spam my attacks. That was when i had the upperhand. You have to go into a fight knowing you will die (obviously), but use that to learn every move or moves that your enemies use and learn them. Its an awesome game.

You have to admit, the PS4 Pro plays this game insanely well considering it only has 4.2 teraflops of processing power and considering the Xbox one x averages around 35 FPS even though it has 6 teraflops. Point being most people can‚Äôt afford a gaming rig bad ass enough to play this game 4K 60 so the best bet for most people would be to buy it for PS4 pro.

snippet.textDisplay:
Due to some really stupid decisions on my part and some very bad luck, I lost my PS4 and T.V.

I'm going really hard looking for a job though. I have an interview on Monday üòÅ!!! I need to get some things taken care of and pay my bills first.

As soon as I'm caught up, the first money that I have that doesn't need to go towards necessities, I am getting a new T.V. and a PS4.

This game is one of the main reasons. I'm also grabbing God of War, Red Dead Redemption II, and Resident Evil II.

I really can't wait. I'm sooooo excited and extremely motivated.

When I had my PS4, the last games I was playing was New Game++ Dark Souls 3, Monster Hunter World, and Terraria.

I definitely have some catching up to do. On my list, but not limited to, are the following: Nier, Hollow Knight, Bloodstained, P.o.E., Death's Gambit, Persona 5, Ni No Kuni II,  Darksiders III, DMC 5, Metro: Exodus, etc. Just to name a few.

Sorry for my whole life story. I just feel like my fellow gamers know where I'm coming from and could share my excitement. As a community, we generally are really supportive of each other and understand the pain of not playing for a while.

Video games truly help me in so many different ways. If  anyone actually read all of this, thank you.

If you want to talk or anything, leave a comment or something. I could definitely use some friends, lol. Other than my brother, I don't really talk to anyone else.

Enough of that though. I can't wait to play this game. Thanks for the video guys. This is like my favorite YT channel. Hard to find trustworthy game journalist, plus I usually agree with their thoughts.

I'll shut up now, lol.

I keep hearing about these frame rate issues..i have had next to none. I wonder why that is. Like some can have issues and others won't. Great review by the way. Loving the game. It's a breath of fresh air from these devs. I love how personal the combat is. And the more nuances to it. The amount of things you can do is really cool and tbh, for a game where ur using only one weapon i was suprised to actually not really miss not have a butt load.

The arm and skills make up for it, i cant wait to see what secrets I'll continue to find.

snippet.textDisplay:
Prosthetic arm, grappling hook, meant-to-win overpowered tutorial boss and a killer chicken...

Guess which two games have these common that recently released?

DMC 5 and Sekiro: Shadows Die Twice
Co-incidence? 

Moreover, the one who fights the killer chicken and the unbeatable tutorial boss in DMC 5 is the same one with the prosthetic arm.

Furthermore, the person responsible for cutting the original arm is pretty much the tutorial boss in both games.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm glad the upgrade system is revamped and has no levels. Bloodborne specifically (because defense increased automatically with levels) had a huge issue with people being like "this was boss was supposed to be hard? I beat him first try" when they were 50 levels above average. I absolutely love the idea of having a uniform experience here that can't be cheesed by level grinding.
